Date: Mon, 23 Nov 98 08:24:04 +0600
From: Sergey V. Netesov <netesov@vector.nsk.su>

This information supplements that which I sent you earlier. It came from
Novosibirsk Regional State Sanitary-Epidemiological Inspection at my
request. Here is the translation of the Russian text of reply prepared by
L. Ivanova, M.D., Deputy Director of the Inspection.
OMSK HEMORRHAGIC FEVER (OHF) IN NOVOSIBIRSK REGION
Cases of hemorrhagic disease of unknown origin first had been registered in
November-December,1961 in Zdvinsk, Barabinsk and Krasnoozersk districts
(counties) of Novosibirsk Region. The massive epizootics among musk-rats
inhabiting small lakes near settlements and after occasional collection of
dead and ill animals preceded human cases of the disease.
The diagnosis of the disease as infectious one and the possible way of
infection was firstly established by the specialists from Omsk Institute of
Natural Foci Infections (Russian Ministry of Public Health). The diagnosis
was confirmed by the isolation of OHF virus from dead animals and
registering the increase of hemagglutination-inhibiting antibody titers to
this virus in the blood of patients.
Cases of human disease cases were not registered between 1962 and 1987.
During the last ten years 152 cases (3 deaths) were registered among
humans. In all the cases the reason of death was because of late starting
of treatment (according to the patient story records. - my comment.SVN).
In 93% of all the cases patients had professional or occasional contacts
with musk-rats (hunting or tearing off the skin) on the lakes of above
mentioned districts, where epizooties were registered.
Novosibirsk Regional State Sanitary-Epidemiological Inspection collaborated
with Omsk Institute of Natural Foci Infections in investigation of
practically all the outbreaks of the disease.
Vaccination against tick-borne encephalitis virus [sic in Ust-Tarka had
been initiated this autumn by Novosibirsk Regional State
Sanitary-Epidemiological Inspection. Instructing professional hunters in
safe handling of musk-rats and their skins was organized by inspection
specialists. Information about this disease and prevention measures,
including vaccination, has been widely distributed among the population of
this area.
Lyubov K. Ivanova, M.D.
Deputy Director of the Inspection.
Novosibirsk Regional State Sanitary-Epidemiological Inspection
[again from Dr. Netesov ...
My comments regarding your comments to my first letter:
1. In Russian edition of Muller's English-Russian and Russian-English
dictionaries there are TWO equivalent translations to Russian word
"ondatra" - muskquash and musk-rat. In Oxford's Dictionary there is only
one - muskrat.
2. Ondatra (muskrat) is so common in Siberia now (I saw this animal a lot
of times in the small rivers and lakes near Novosibirsk) that only
specialists know that it had been imported from American continent.
3. Of course, the virologists in Russia know that OHF virus is close to TBE
in antigenic properties and by genome sequences. Therefore this decision
about vaccination was made. As for CEE (or TBE or RSSE) vaccines: there
are two inactivated chromatographically purified vaccines produced in
Russia: one in Moscow Institute of Poliomyelitis and Viral Encephalitis
with Sofjin strain of TBE [Sofjin is the prototype strain of Russian
Spring-Summer encephalitis virus - Mod.CHC virus, the second - in Tomsk
NPO "Virion" on the base of 205 TBE strain [unknown to me - Mod.CHC.
Austrian inactivated and chromatographically purified vaccine is produced
by IMMUNO company with strain Neudorfl [the standard western European
strain of Central European encephalitis virus - Mod.CHC.
The genome sequences of all three strains were published in the middle of
1980s and are similar to each other (from 5% - Sofjin-205 - to 16.3% -
205-Neudorfl - homology in amino acid sequences of E-protein).
There are no proven data regarding comparison of all these vaccines in
field studies.
--
Sergey V.Netesov, Prof.
Deputy Director (Research)
State Research Center of Virology and Biotechnology VECTOR
633159 Novosibirsk Region, p.Koltsovo
Russia
