Date: Saturday, November 21, 1998 1:24PM
From: C.J. Peters <cjp0@cdc.gov>

Kertie Shah and others tested TBE vaccine vs. Kyasanur Forest disease (KFD)
both in the lab and in the field without success. KFD is now controlled, at
least in lab workers, by use of a killed vaccine against that virus. For a
good summary of recent work on the genetic relationships of the TBE complex
see the article by Gould, de Andrade Zanatto, and Holmes, "The genetic
evolution of flaviviruses", pp 51-63 in Factors in the Emergence of
Arbovirus Diseases, ed JF Saluzzo and B Dodet, Elsevier, 1997 or their
original publications. They show that OHF virus is closer genetically (but
not necessarily antigenically) to TBE than is KFD virus. Although CEE and
RSSE are considered to be essentially the same virus by some and although
these two clearly cross-protect in the lab, I have never seen any field
data that addresses whether a killed vaccine against one will protect
humans from the other.
--
C.J. Peters
Special Pathogens Branch
Division of Viral and Rickettsial Diseases
Center for Infectious Diseases
U.S. Centers for Disease Control and Prevention
Atlanta, GA
e-mail: cjp0@cdc.gov
[3
Date: Mon Nov 23 14:11:39 1998
From: Irina Gavrilovskaya <IRINA@mail.som.sunysb.edu>

Some historical notes:
Omsk hemorrhagic fever virus (OHFV) was isolated from _Ixodes marginatus-
ticks and from patient's blood by Professor MP Chumakov et al. in 1947. The
first description of this hitherto unknown disease was made in 1946 by
clinician Galina Sizemova and epidemiologist Anna Gavrilovskaya. They
described a winter 1944 outbreak among hunters for ondatra (Ondatra
zibethicus) [musk-rat, musquash, muskrat. The hunters prepared the
ondatras in their homes and used the meat for food because of shortage of
food during the war time.
The disease was characterized by high fever and profuse lung and uterine
hemorrhages. Often two-wave course of the disease occurred. In 1947 the
great spring-summer outbreak of OHF was registered among agriculture
workers in the forest-steppe locations of the Omsk region (listed by Dr.
Netesof); mortality was about 10%. The season of outbreak followed the
cycle of _Ix. marginatus_. In 1948 another outbreak occurred. In that
summer vaccination of the rural adult population of the endemic areas was
made with OHF virus vaccine prepared from infected mice brains.
After vaccination no outbreaks were described but sporadic cases were
reported among ondatra hunters in Omsk and Novosibirsk regions. OHF virus
was regularly isolated from ondatras, ticks and field mice. Serologically,
OHF and Tick-borne encephalitis (TBE) viruses are very similar. First data
about serodifferentiation of these viruses were determined by D. Clark
[Delphine Clarke at Rockefeller Institute, many years ago. - Mod.CHC in
diffuse immunoprecipitation and later by me in neutralization test in PS
[porcine stable cells. Differentiation of these viruses is important
because often there is a co-localization of their endemic areas.
--
Irina Gavrilovskaya, PhD MD
Department of Medicine/GI
State University of New York at Stony Brook
HSC T17, Rm 060
Stony Brook, NY11794
TEL: (516) 444-7779
e-mail: Irina@mail.som.sunysb.edu
[Our readers are greatly appreciative of the timely input by these three
experts. As you can see, the term "TBE" is a confusing one and should be
discarded, except as the (poor) name for the disease. Using a single name
for more than one virus is very misleading with respect to vaccine efficacy.
It remains to be seen whether this outbreak of OHF is simply one of
numerous sporadic occurrences or whether it will be shown to have spread
from a focus. I will not comment on the use of vaccines prepared from
virus amplified in mouse brains but I wouldn't take one. - Mod.CHC
...............chc/es
